Aim:
To write a C++ program that demonstrates the use of manipulators such as setw(), setprecision(), fixed, and endl.

Algorithm:
Start the program.
Include <iostream> and <iomanip> header files.
Declare variables of different types.
Use manipulators like setw() to format output width.
Use fixed and setprecision() to control decimal points.
Display the formatted output.
End the program.

Program
#include <iostream>
#include <iomanip>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int a = 25, b = 300, c = 1250;
    double x = 45.6789;
    cout << "Demonstrating setw():\n";
    cout << setw(5) << a << endl;
    cout << setw(5) << b << endl;
    cout << setw(5) << c << endl;
    cout << "\nDemonstrating setprecision() and fixed:\n";
    cout << fixed << setprecision(2) << x << endl;
    return 0;
}

Output:
Demonstrating setw():
   25
  300
 1250
Demonstrating setprecision() and fixed:
45.68

Result:
Thus, manipulators like setw(), setprecision(), and fixed were successfully demonstrated using a C++ program.

